oc:kn_2ec1c349 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When defining or applying brand communication" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Voice is consistent personality; Tone is how voice adapts to context. A brand has one voice but many tones depending on the situation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Confusing voice with tone leads to inconsistent branding — voice stays fixed while tone flexes per context" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_4077b4df a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building voice guidelines or charts" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never create a voice chart without both 'Do' and 'Don't' columns. Anti-examples are as important as examples for guiding consistent voice." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without explicit 'don't' examples, writers often overshoot personality traits into negative territory (friendly→unprofessional, confident→arrogant)" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_95b140e6 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When developing brand personality traits" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Choose exactly 3-5 personality traits for a brand voice. Each trait needs a paired boundary (e.g., 'Confident, not arrogant')." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Too few traits make the voice generic; too many make it unfocused. Boundaries prevent traits from sliding into negative territory." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_c6b4235b a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When reviewing or testing any brand copy" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Validate voice consistency by asking: (1) Does this sound like our brand? (2) Would a competitor say this? (3) Does it resonate with our audience? (4) Is it consistent with our values?" ;
    oc:hasRationale "These four questions catch voice drift, generic messaging, audience mismatch, and value misalignment respectively" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_dd7783b2 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When adapting brand voice to different channels or situations" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Map tone shifts across four spectrums: Formal↔Casual, Simple↔Complex, Serious↔Playful, Reserved↔Expressive. Adjust position based on context (social media→casual, legal→formal, support→empathetic, sales→confident)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Spectrums provide a systematic way to calibrate tone without losing the underlying voice identity" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

